==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Ware
<hw>Ware</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>ware</ets>, AS.
<ets>waru</ets>; akin to D. <ets>waar</ets>, G. <ets>waare</ets>, Icel.
& Sw. <ets>vara</ets>, Dan. <ets>vare</ets>; and probably to E.
<ets>worth</ets>, a. See <er>Worth</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>
<def>Articles of merchandise; the sum of articles of a particular kind
or class; style or class of manufactures; especially, in the plural,
goods; commodities; merchandise.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Retails his
<xex>wares</xex> at wakes.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧To chaffer with
them and eke to sell them their <xex>ware</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It the people of the land bring <qex>ware</qex> or any victuals on
the Sabbath day to sell, that we would not buy it of them on the
Sabbath, or on the holy day.</q> <rj><qau>Neh. x. 31.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Although originally and properly a collective noun, it
admits of a plural form, when articles of merchandise of different kinds
are meant. It is often used in composition; as in hard<xex>ware</xex>,
glass<xex>ware</xex>, tin<xex>ware</xex>, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ware</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Ware
<hw>Ware</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>war</ets>, AS.
<ets>w⟦ae⟧r</ets>. ⟦root⟧142. See <er>Wary</er>.]</ety> <def>A ware;
taking notice; hence, wary; cautious; on one's guard. See
<er>Beware</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She was <qex>ware</qex> and knew it bet [better] than he.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of whom be thou <qex>ware</qex> also.</q> <rj><qau>2. Tim. iv.
15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is <qex>ware</qex> enough; he is wily and circumspect for
stirring up any sedition.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The only good that grows of passed fear⟦br⟧
Is to be wise, and <qex>ware</qex> of like again.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ware</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Ware
<hw>Ware</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>waru</ets> caution.]</ety>
<def>The state of being ware or aware; heed.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Wyclif.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ware</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Ware
<hw>Ware</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[As. <ets>warian</ets>.]</ety>
<def>To make ware; to warn; to take heed of; to beware of; to guard
against.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Ware</xex> that I say.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God . . . <qex>ware</qex> you for the sin of avarice.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then <qex>ware</qex> a rising tempest on the main.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wareful</ent>⟦br⟧
